06481nam a22006975i 9781503616660DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221997cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036166607 a10.1515/97815036166602doi  a(DE-B1597)581823  a(OCoLC)1312726373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0000002bisacsh00aViolence, Identity, and Self-Determination /ced. by Hent de Vries, Samuel Weber. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tViolence and Testimony: On Sacrificing Sacrifice -- tMonastic Violence -- tCharacteristic Violencei or, The Physiognomy of Style -- tWartime -- tThe Camp as the Nomos of the Modern -- tEnlightenment and Paranomia -- tCannibals All: The Grave Wit of Kant's Perpetual Peace -- tOtherwise than Self-Determination: The Mortal Freedom of Oedipus Asphaleos -- tThe Victim's Tale: Memory and Forgetting in the Story of Violence -- tEroticism, Colonialism, and Violence -- tTraumatic Awakenings -- tHabeas Corpus: The Law's Desire to Have the Body -- tOn the Politics of Pure Means: Benjamin, Arendt, Foucault -- tMarx, Mourning, Messianicity -- tViolence, Identity, Self-Determination, and the Question of Justice: on Specters of Marx -- tOne 2 Many Multiculturalisms -- t... and pomegranates -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the collapse of the bipolar system of global rivalry that dominated world politics after the Second World War, and in an age that is seeing the return of "ethnic cleansing" and "identity politics," the question of violence, in all of its multiple ramifications, imposes itself with renewed urgency. Rather than concentrating on the socioeconomic or political backgrounds of these historical changes, the contributors to this volume rethink the concept of violence, both in itself and in relation to the formation and transformation of identities, whether individual or collective, political or cultural, religious or secular. In particular, they subject the notion of self-determination to stringent scrutiny: is it to be understood as a value that excludes violence, in principle if not always in practice? Or is its relation to violence more complex and, perhaps, more sinister? Reconsideration of the concepts, the practice, and even the critique of violence requires an exploration of the implications and limitations of the more familiar interpretations of the terms that have dominated in the history of Western thought. To this end, the nineteen contributors address the concept of violence from a variety of perspectives in relation to different forms of cultural representation, and not in Western culture alone; in literature and the arts, as well as in society and politics; in philosophical discourse, psychoanalytic theory, and so-called juridical ideology, as well as in colonial and post-colonial practices and power relations. The contributors are Giorgio Agamben, Ali Behdad, Cathy Caruth, Jacques Derrida, Michael Dillon, Peter Fenves, Stathis Gourgouris, Werner Hamacher, Beatrice Hanssen, Anselm Haverkamp, Marian Hobson, Peggy Kamuf, M. B. Pranger, Susan M. Shell, Peter van der Veer, Hent de Vries, Cornelia Vismann, and Samuel Weber.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAgamben, Giorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehdad, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaruth, Cathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Vries, Hent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov